        "simpler": "Kids learn how to cope mostly by watching the grown-ups they love. When you calmly name your feelings, take a slow breath, or say out loud, I am frustrated, so I will pause, you teach coping better than any lecture. You do not have to be perfectly calm. Just show, honestly, how you calm yourself back down.",
        "deeper": "Coping strategies are acquired in large part through observational learning. When a caregiver labels their own emotional states and demonstrates a regulation strategy in real time, the child observes a concrete model of affect identification followed by an adaptive response. The instructive element is not the absence of distress but the visible enactment of recovery, which gives the child a template to imitate."
